<Content>Elegant and good service Mexico City is a big dirty crowded city. The Four Seasons is an oasis of calm and elegance in the middle of this. The hotel is built in a square around a large open-air courtyard containing tropical gardens, a fountain, sculptures, a cafe, and a restaurant. It is worth paying the extra to get an inward facing room overlooking the courtyard instead of an outward-facing room with a street view.The hotel lives up to the Four Seasons standard. The rooms are large, traditional, and understatedly elegant. They have all the amentities and features that you would expect. We travelled with our baby and thought it was lovely the way they set up a crib with toys, baby products, and a hand-written sign with our baby's name.The public areas of the hotel are also very spacious and elegant. The gym is small but has modern equipment, refreshments, and everything you need for an adequate on-the-road workout. There is a nice but small (definitely not for swimming laps!) rooftop pool surrounding by beachchairs for relaxing in the sunshine.The service was generally excellent - smiling, friendly people doing everything possible to make your stay comfortable. Our only niggle was the up-selling on check-in. We arrived early and were offered an early check-in if we paid for an extra day. Since we were staying for a week, I would expect early check-in to be offered for free if a room was ready. We were also offered a variety of room upgrade options for a price. I felt like I was at a rental car counter, not an upscale hotel!Overall, I definitely recommend the Four Seasons in Mexico City. We have also stayed at the JW Marriott in Mexico City. That is a nice hotel, but the Four Seasons is in a class above it in terms of both surroundings and service. 
