<Content>Lovely Hotel We are just back from three days at the Four Seasons Mexico City and had a lovely time. The hotel has a web promotional rate for three day stays (Thursday, Friday and Saturday nights only) that is exceptional. The offer extends to their suites.The condition of the property is excellent and the photos on the website are accurate.We booked the hotel's airport pick up driver and were very happy with the service and the driver's skill.We had breakfast, dinner through room service and dinner in the restaurant and it was above average but not stellar. Breakfast for two off the menu ran $60, not unusual at a businessman's hotel, but dinner was quite reasonable.The most exceptional thing about our stay was the service. The staff is exceptionally well trained, skilled, friendly and unpretentious.The hotel felt secure (with card entry to the room access corridors and to the guest rooms) and elegant.We have stayed in at least 6 Four Seasons Hotels throughout the world and felt that the Mexico City property was unfortunately a bit of a step down from their usual standard.There were two things that stood out. The first is that they use the ubiquitous comforters on the bed, with an embroidered sheet cover and a folded throw on top. All of that is fine except that they don't use a duvet to enclose the comforters. Instead they use your top sheet as the bottom of the cover of the comforter, so there really isn't a top (flat) sheet on the bed. They are using a flat embroidered sheet on top of the comforter and your top sheet as the bottom of the comforter. So if you disarrange the flat sheet you have the raw comforter on you. Which, for me was a bit of an ewwwwww. I don't want to be wondering when the last time the comforter was washed.This is just weird and not something that you expect from the Four Seasons. Perhaps this is a result of the water shortage.The other odd thing was that the shower stall is about 2 1/2 foot square, but the bathroom is huge.They must have used the same architect at the San Francisco Four Seasons, because that property has the same flaw.We liked the property, mainly because of the staff.Anyway, the property is nice, but don't expect the Georges V.PS: Mexico City now closes Reforma on Sundays to auto trafficso that bicyclists, skaters and runners can use the boulevard for fun.It really gives the area a festive and accessible feel. 
