<Author>eaglehaslanded
<Content>A great hotel The Four Seasons in Mexico City, for all its problems, remains a fantastic hotel. Its value is greatly increased if you book during an off-peak period, when rates can be significantly lower.Service is unparalleled. As with many other Four Seasons properties, staff are trained to get to know you and fulfill your needs beyond your expectations. By and large this is the case, particularly if cost is not an issue. The concierge service, for example, can provide you with a car and driver any time, any day, any hour... if you are willing to pay $28 an hour ($33 if he is to provide explanations), rather than the $11 an hour charged by a regular taxi (which the concierge will be willing to get for you, no questions asked--although it's worth noting that you may get some very un-Four Seasons-like attitude from the bellboys for having the temerity to go the low-class ordinary taxi route).As for food, the news is mixed. The service at the Four Seasons bar is excellent if you go when there are few other patrons; it is, otherwise, severely understaffed, leading to frustrated guests. Room service is limited in its options; having tried different items from its menus over a period of five days, it is reasonably safe to say that the Italian menu items are mediocre at best. Though beautifully presented, they are nowhere near the level that you would expect from a hotel of this caliber. Morning coffee is often stale, evening coffee even worse. In fact, the only saving grace with respect to food in this hotel is a spectacular pastry chef, who serves chocolate croissants that are to die for.Why then, the five star review? It's pretty simple: this is likely the best hotel in the city. The service remains extraordinary: yes, room service may get your order wrong, and the quality may be poor. But bottom line is that they will try to fulfill any oddball request you might have--and indeed, by the time you leave, you feel as if you would expect to have your whims fulfilled by them. And the same is true of the concierge, drivers, waiters, and just about everyone else at the hotel (except the bellboy staff if you order a taxi).The rooms are cleaned and _organized_ not once, but twice, and possibly thrice a day. Housekeeping is possibly the best I have ever seen at any hotel I have ever stayed at.The staff of chauffeurs, too, is top notch, beginning (but likely not ending) with the excellent Edmundo.Finally, Mexico City is a huge city, loud, and ultimately draining for the average tourist. It's a cliche repeated by others who come to this hotel, but it really is an oasis in that city. When you're done with a morning and afternoon's events, having a late coffee in the hotel's courtyard (served by fantastic waiters like the hotel's Jes煤s) is genuinely soothing. And coming to your room is truly restful. You can't ask for too much more than that. 
